ce:section.ce:para:
An attempt has also been made to investigate the antibacterial potential of SCDs against both gram positive (S. aureus and S. mutans) and gram negative (E. coli and K. pneumonia) bacterial pathogens through agar well diffusion assay. The results inferred that, SCDs effectively suppressed the growth of S. aureus and S. mutans, resulting in inhibitory zones ranged between 10 and 11 mm at lower concentration (50 μg/mL); nevertheless, at higher concentration (100 μg/mL) the inhibitory zones increased to 13 and 14 mm, respectively. Conversely, SCDs exerted marginally reduced growth inhibitory activity against E. coli (10–11 mm) and K. pnuemoniae (10–11 mm). This tends to indicate that antagonistic activity of SCDs is significantly higher against gram positive pathogens rather than gram negative strains. This could be attributed to variation in cell wall composition between these bacterial strains (Fig. 4
                     ). The antibacterial activity observed in the present study is notably superior to that reported by Ma et al., (2020), who showed antibacterial activity of Osmanthus leaves derived N-doped CDs against E. coli and S. aureus at 1000 μg/mL. According to a study by Pandiyan et al. (2022) CDs adhere to the surface of bacterial cell wall and slowly penetrate the cell wall and binds to DNA, causing unwinding of the duplex DNA and thereby attenuating the bacterial pathogen and substantiates antimicrobial property. Ghirardello et al. (2021) emphasized that CDs are excellent source towards combating the emergence of multidrug resistant bacterial strains (Ghirardello et al., 2021) due to the unique characteristics of SCDs viz. Biocompatibility, minimal toxicity and solubility in water. Significant precision advantages are evident when compared to other techniques, as demonstrated in Table 1
                     .
